11th Street, west side, south from 51st Avenue to Borden Avenue. This block, among others, was later cleared of all buildings and made part of the Queens-Midtown Tunnel Plaza; the tunnel's toll booths were erected here.

November 17, 1938

New York City Tunnel Authority

11th Street, east side, north from 51st to 50th Avenues. The corner lot marks the northern edge of the new concrete road that will be laid out here leading from the Queens-Midtown Tunnel. The road will sweep across the frame dwelling (and others) beyond the lot and will lead out toward the distant points of Queens.

November 18, 1938

New York City Tunnel Authority

11th Street, adjoining the S. W. corner of 51st Avenue, showing a sheet-metal garage nestling against a row of tenements. These were later razed and the whole area reconstructed as the plaza of the Queens-Midtown Tunnel; the tunnel's toll booths were erected on this site.

November 21, 1938

New York City Tunnel Authority

11th Street, east side, south from 51st to Borden Avenues. This area was later made part of the plaza of the Queens-Midtown Tunnel.

November 17, 1938

New York City Tunnel Authority

11th Street, east side, south from 51st Avenue to Borden Avenue. This area was later incorporated into the broad concrete highway leading to the Queens-Midtown Tunnel entrance, a block away.

November 22, 1938.
New York City Tunnel Authority

11th Street (right), west side, north from 51st to 50th Avenues. The buildings on the left are nos. 10-53 to 10-49 51st Avenue. All these houses were later demolished and on the site was erected the Service Building of the Queens-Midtown Tunnel.

November 18, 1938

New York City Tunnel Authority

10-35 to 10-27 51st Avenue, north side, between 11th Street and Jackson Avenue, looking west toward the latter. This photograph is one of a number that was taken to show the type of housing that prevailed in this area when the Queens-Midtown Tunnel was cut through. A number of dwellings similar to these were demolished, these, however, were spared.

November 21, 1938

New York City Tunnel Authority

10-38 and 10-40 51st Avenue, south side, between 11th Street and 'ackson Avenue, showing two frame houses which, among others, were later torn down to make way for the construction of the Queens-Midtown Tunnel.

November 21, 1938

New York City Tunnel Authority

10-38 to 10-42 51st Avenue, south side, between 11th Street and Jackson Avenue, showing three frame houses that were later demolished when the entire block of buildings were razed to make way for the construction of the sunken plaza of the Queens-Midtown Tunnel.

November 21, 1938

New York City Tunnel Authority

10-46 51st Avenue, west of the S. W. corner of 11th Street. This is one of a group of houses of similar architecture which was torn down, together with houses comprising the rest of the block, to make way for the construction of the Queens-Midtown Tunnel.

November 11, 1938

New York City Tunnel Authority

10-50 51st Avenue, west of the S.W. corner of 11th Street, showing one of a row of five similar houses which was later torn down when this area was converted into the plaza of the Queens-Midtown Tunnel.

November 21, 1938

New York City Tunnel Authority

10-34 51st Avenue, south side, between 11th Street and Jackson Avenue, showing one of a group of frame houses which was torn down when this area was being converted into the plaza of the Queens-Midtown Tunnel.

November 21, 1938

New York City Tunnel Authority

51st Avenue, south side, between 11th and 21st Streets, viewing toward the latter and showing a scrap metal yard. This part of the thoroughfare and the yard were later obliterated and the new highway leading from the Queens-Midtown Tunnel thrown across here.

November 22, 1938

New York City Tunnel Authority

51st Avenue, east from 11th Street, showing, on the south side of the avenue, a dumping lot and a scrap metal yard and some factory buildings at 21st Street. Across the unoccupied area was later constructed the highway leading to the Queens-Midtown Tunnel entrance, a block away. The new highway will cut across the view from the lower right hand corner to the left center background.

November 11, 1938

New York City Tunnel Authority

51st Avenue, east from 11th Street. This area later became part of the newly constructed approach to the Queens-Midtown Tunnel, which necessitated the demolition of the buildings seen in this view, with the exception of those in the right background.

November 21, 1938

New York City Tunnel Authority

51st Avenue, north side, east from 11th Street. The corner plot and the whole area extending across the frame dwelling and the one-story adjoining buildings were made part of the new highway leading from the Queens-Midtown Tunnel after the dwellings were razed. The houses in the left foreground were left untouched.

November 18, 1938

New York City Tunnel Authority

51st Avenue, north side, west from 11th Street. The first six houses, Nos. 10-53 to 10-43, were razed and on their site was erected the Service Building of the Queens-Midtown Tunnel.

November 17, 1938

New York City Tunnel Authority

51st Avenue, south side, west from 11th Street. All these buildings were later torn down and the site was converted into the sunken plaza of the Queens-Midtown Tunnel.

November 17, 1938

New York City Tunnel Authority

10-48 51st Avenue, west of the S.W. corner of 11th Street, showing one of several similar houses which was torn down to make way for the construction, on this site, of the Queens-Midtown Tunnel plaza.

November 11, 1938

New York City Tunnel Authority

51st Avenue, north side, between 11th and 21st Streets. The view is northeastward across the line of the elevated highway, which was later thrown across here, leading from the Queens-Midtown Tunnel. To the right of the Long Island Railroad tracks is a Sheffield Farms Company building; on the left is the Queens-Borough Hall, and in the center background is the 49th Avenue vehicular viaduct.

November 11, 1938

New York City Tunnel Authority

51st Avenue, north side, (foreground) between 11th and 21st Streets, looking northeastward across the area which marks the direct path of the highway leading from the Queens-Midtown Tunnel, later built here. The row of tenements--the rears of which are seen--fronting on the south side of 50th Avenue were later demolished. In the right background is the Queens Borough Hall on 21st Street, corner of 49th Avenue.

November 21, 1938

New York City Tunnel Authority

51st Avenue (foreground), north side, between 21st and 11th Streets, viewing northwestward across the clearance which later became part of the highway leading from the Queens-Midtown Tunnel. Shown, too, are the rears of dwellings on the south side of 50th Avenue which were later razed. In the left background appears the steeple of St. Marys Roman Catholic Church.

November 21, 1938

New York City Tunnel Authority

51st Avenue, south side, between 21st and 11th Streets (vantage point). This is a general view southwestward in a direct line of the elevated highway, which will be constructed here to carry vehicular traffic to and from the Queens Midtown Tunnel.

November 21, 1938

New York City Tunnel Authority

51st Avenue, south side (foreground), between 21st and 11th Streets. The view is southwestward across the clearance (this side of the Long Island Railroad tracks) which marks the line of the new highway leading into the Queens-Midtown Tunnel. On the left is a portion of the Mavis Building and a railroad water tower.

November 18, 1938

New York City Tunnel Authority

51st Avenue, at 11th Street, viewing southwestward and showing, under construction, the toll-booth gates to the Queens-Midtown Tunnel.

P. L. Sperr
July 27, 1940
